The concept of NP-completeness is a theoretical classification in computational complexity theory that deals with the difficulty of solving certain problems efficiently.

The problem of determining whether a given number of moves is sufficient to solve a Rubik's Cube has been shown to be NP-complete.

Another example is the Boolean satisfiability problem, which involves finding an assignment of values to variables that satisfies a set of Boolean constraints. This problem has been proven to be NP-complete by Cook in 1971.

The problem of determining whether a given graph contains a Hamiltonian cycle is also known to be NP-complete. A Hamiltonian cycle is a path in the graph that visits each vertex exactly once before returning to the starting vertex.

The traveling salesman problem, which involves finding the shortest possible tour that visits a set of cities and returns to the starting city, has been shown to be NP-complete.

Another example is the 3-Satisfiability problem, which is a variant of the Boolean satisfiability problem in which each variable can take on only three values. This problem has also been proven to be NP-complete by Tovey in 1986.

The problem of determining whether a given set of points in Euclidean space can be separated by a hyperplane is known as the max clique problem, and it has been shown to be NP-complete.
